Week 28 unfolded as a week of consolidation rather than shock. The surface picture was one of continuity: the same president, the same Congress, the same courts. Yet beneath that surface, the architecture of power shifted another notch toward a system in which law, money, and information serve the executive first and the public only incidentally. The week\'92s events did not hinge on a single spectacular order or crisis. Instead, they formed a dense web of moves\'97tariff decrees, funding freezes, detention practices, and appointments\'97that together made it harder to see where neutral governance ended and personal rule began. The state\'92s basic promises\'97equal citizenship, independent courts, a professional civil service\'97were not abolished. They were bent further to fit the needs of one man and his circle.\
\
At the close of Week 27, the Democracy Clock stood at 7:53 p.m., already deep into the evening of the constitutional day. By the end of Week 28, the public time remained 7:53 p.m., yet the underlying measure crept forward by 0.2 minutes. The face of the clock did not move, but the mechanism did. That small internal advance captures the character of the week. There was no single break that would force the hand to jump. Instead, there was a thickening of patterns already present: law used as a weapon rather than a limit, citizenship stratified by ancestry and status, the civil service and judiciary filled and disciplined for loyalty, universities and media brought to heel through money and regulation, and emergency economic tools normalized as instruments of routine policy. The system still resembled a democracy in form. In function, it edged further toward something else.\
\
The most visible strand of that shift ran through the law itself. Across the week, the administration treated statutes and legal tools less as constraints than as flexible instruments for punishing enemies and managing risk. The Alien Enemies Act of 1798, a relic from the early republic, was invoked to deport Venezuelan migrants accused of gang ties without hearings or warrants. Justice Department lawyers argued that the Act allowed raids and removals without court review, and planes carrying deportees continued to El Salvador despite a federal judge\'92s order to return them. At the same time, a new detention camp in the Everglades\'97nicknamed Alligator Alcatraz\'97held hundreds of people without charges, access to lawyers, or bond hearings. When civil rights lawyers sought emergency relief, they were told the court lacked jurisdiction. In both cases, the message was the same. For certain categories of people, law would not be a shield; it would be the language in which their exclusion was justified.\
\
This instrumental view of law extended beyond immigration. The Department of Justice filed a misconduct complaint against a federal judge, James Boasberg, for public comments about the administration, signaling that judges who spoke candidly about executive conduct could face formal discipline. At the same time, the attorney general\'92s office pressed courts to unseal grand jury transcripts in the Epstein and Maxwell cases, while other parts of the federal apparatus ordered Trump\'92s name redacted from related files and pressured the FBI records chief who objected into retirement. The administration floated the possibility of a pardon for Ghislaine Maxwell and sent a senior deputy attorney general to interview her, even as victims and lawmakers demanded assurances that no clemency would be offered. Law, in this pattern, became a set of levers: secrecy here, selective transparency there, discipline for a critical judge, leniency for a well-connected defendant.\
\
Citizenship itself was narrowed in theory and in practice. Vice President J.D. Vance used a speech at the Claremont Institute to argue that American citizenship should be rooted in blood and soil, suggesting that those whose ancestors fought in the Civil War had a greater claim to the nation than more recent arrivals. The Department of Homeland Security amplified this vision by posting the 19th-century painting \'93American Progress,\'94 with a caption celebrating a \'93Heritage to be proud of, a Homeland worth Defending,\'94 and by repurposing a contemporary religious painting without the artist\'92s consent to evoke nationalist sentiment. These symbolic gestures were matched by policy. The administration moved to strip legal status from more than a million immigrants by terminating the CHNV parole program and ramping up arrests, urged DACA recipients to \'93self-deport\'94 despite no regulatory change, and announced SNAP changes that would shift costs to states and tighten eligibility for non-citizens. In detention, a double-amputee from Liberia was placed in solitary confinement for refusing to enter a flooded area that threatened his prosthetic legs. Together, these actions hardened a tiered system in which ancestry, nationality, and identity determined not only one\'92s chances in life, but the degree of protection the law would offer.\
\
The civil service, long designed as a buffer between politics and administration, came under sharper partisan control. The week saw the firing of the Commissioner of Labor Statistics after a weak jobs report that the president denounced as \'93rigged.\'94 She was to be replaced by a political appointee, signaling that official economic data would henceforth be judged not by methodological rigor but by whether it flattered the White House narrative. At the Food and Drug Administration, the top vaccine and gene therapy official resigned after a public campaign against him led by a right-wing activist, and the head of the White House Office of Pandemic Preparedness resigned after revealing he had never been formally appointed at all. The Office of Personnel Management issued guidance allowing federal employees to pray publicly at work and to persuade colleagues of their religious views, blurring the line between personal faith and public duty. In the national security sphere, the top lawyer at the National Security Agency was fired after right-wing media labeled her a \'93far-left Democrat activist\'94 based on her past work for Senate Democrats. These moves did not abolish the civil service. They bent it, making clear that tenure and expertise offered less protection than ideological alignment.\
