The judiciary, too, moved another step away from independence. The Senate confirmed Emil Bove, a former Trump defense attorney and senior Justice Department official, to a lifetime seat on the federal appeals court by a 50\'9649 vote. This came despite whistleblower allegations that he had urged colleagues to ignore court orders regarding migrant flights and misled Congress about dropping corruption charges against the mayor of New York. More than eighty judges and multiple whistleblowers had raised concerns about his fitness. The confirmation went forward anyway, with the Republican majority treating loyalty as a credential rather than a warning sign. At the same time, the Justice Department maneuvered to keep loyal U.S. attorneys in place by designating interim prosecutors as acting just before their statutory terms expired, preventing district judges from appointing replacements. In New Jersey, questions about the legality of Alina Habba\'92s appointment as acting U.S. attorney led to the cancellation of federal criminal proceedings. The pattern was clear. Prosecutorial power would remain in trusted hands, and the bench would be stocked with those who had already demonstrated a willingness to bend law to executive needs.\
\
Against this backdrop, Congress looked smaller and more reactive. In Washington, House Speaker Mike Johnson adjourned the chamber early to avoid a vote on releasing Epstein files, even as members of both parties called for more transparency. In Missouri, a Republican supermajority moved to repeal or weaken multiple voter-approved measures on Medicaid expansion, marijuana, abortion rights, and animal welfare, prompting a bipartisan backlash from citizens who saw their votes being undone. In North Carolina, the General Assembly overrode the governor\'92s vetoes on bills easing environmental rules for a major utility, tightening immigration enforcement, and restricting recognition of gender identities beyond male and female. The same legislature rescheduled a hearing on a voter suppression bill to a time that would limit public attendance. In Texas, Republicans unveiled a congressional map designed to give their party five additional seats, targeting districts with large minority populations. These were not isolated acts of partisanship. They were pieces of a broader pattern in which legislatures functioned less as deliberative bodies and more as instruments for entrenching power, often at the expense of direct democratic decisions and fair representation.\
\
Universities and schools became central battlegrounds in this struggle over power and narrative. The administration froze $108 million in federal research funding to Duke University over alleged racial discrimination in affirmative action, and reached a settlement with Columbia University that required a $221 million payment and a pledge not to consider race, color, sex, or national origin in hiring in order to restore $1.3 billion in previously withheld funds. At the same time, the Department of Education and other agencies mandated antisemitism trainings at universities, designed by pro-Israel groups and criticized for equating anti-Zionism with antisemitism, as a condition for federal funding. These trainings were rolled out at Northwestern, Columbia, Harvard, and other campuses under the threat of investigations and funding cuts. The Department of Justice sent letters to Duke and George Mason University scrutinizing diversity and equity policies, and the administration launched an investigation into the Duke Law Journal over alleged race-based preferences. In Oklahoma, the state schools chief announced that teachers from \'93liberal\'94 states would have to pass a \'93MAGA Exam,\'94 developed with a conservative media outfit, to be certified. Together, these moves used money, accreditation, and regulatory scrutiny to narrow the range of acceptable ideas in education, not by banning dissent outright, but by making it costly.\
