The executive\'92s reach into economic life widened through a series of tariff orders and fiscal maneuvers that blurred the line between emergency and routine policy. Over the course of the week, the president declared a national emergency over Brazil\'92s treatment of Jair Bolsonaro and imposed an additional 40 percent duty on certain Brazilian imports, suspended duty-free treatment for all low-value imports, and issued an order \'93further modifying\'94 reciprocal tariff rates on multiple trading partners. New tariffs of 10 to 25 percent were announced on goods from India, the Philippines, Indonesia, South Korea, Japan, the United Kingdom, and others, often tied to grievances over trade deficits, energy purchases from Russia, or foreign policy positions such as Canada\'92s recognition of Palestinian statehood. A separate order raised tariffs on Canadian goods from 25 to 35 percent and imposed a 40 percent levy on transshipped goods, citing both drug trafficking and political disagreements. These measures were justified under emergency and national security statutes, particularly the International Emergency Economic Powers Act, even as a federal appeals court heard arguments that such use of IEEPA exceeded congressional intent. In practice, they allowed the president to rewire global trade flows and raise consumer prices without new legislation, while claiming credit for \'93deals\'94 whose terms were often vague or misrepresented.\
