At the same time, domestic fiscal tools were repurposed to concentrate power. The administration explored \'93pocket rescissions\'94 to withhold funds Congress had already allocated by sending rescission requests late enough that the money would expire before lawmakers could act. A rescissions package signed earlier in the term had already cut previously appropriated education funds, testing the limits of the Impoundment Control Act. National Institutes of Health research grants were impounded and then partially restored after internal pushback, demonstrating how scientific work could be stalled or advanced at the pleasure of the White House. The Treasury secretary described new \'93Trump accounts\'94 created by budget reconciliation as a \'93backdoor for privatizing Social Security,\'94 signaling a long-term strategy to shift a core public pension program into market-based accounts without a direct vote on privatization. The Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program was restructured so that states would shoulder 75 percent of administrative costs by 2027 and a share of benefits thereafter, while work reporting requirements were expanded and non-citizen eligibility narrowed. These changes did not abolish the welfare state. They hollowed it, moving risk and cost downward to households and states while preserving federal discretion and donor-friendly tax cuts.\
\
Regulatory agencies, formally designed to balance public and private interests, were further drawn into the orbit of executive and corporate priorities. Staff at the newly created Department of Government Efficiency deployed an AI tool\'97the DOGE AI Deregulation Decision Tool\'97to generate a \'93delete list\'94 of federal regulations, with a goal of eliminating half of all rules by January. The tool had already been used to drive decisions at the Department of Housing and Urban Development and the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau. Its criteria were opaque, its operation shielded from public input. At the Environmental Protection Agency, leadership moved to revoke the 2009 greenhouse gas endangerment finding, which underpinned federal authority to regulate climate pollution, and issued an interim rule extending compliance deadlines for emissions standards in the oil and gas sector. The Interior Department ended subsidies for wind and solar energy, arguing that renewables had enjoyed \'93preferential treatment.\'94 The Securities and Exchange Commission approved a gun company backed by Donald Trump Jr. to trade publicly shortly after the new Trump-appointed chair attended a launch party for another Trump Jr. venture. The Federal Communications Commission approved a major media merger on the condition that the new entity avoid civil rights programming and install a political bias monitor. In each case, the formal processes of rulemaking and review remained. But their direction tilted: away from environmental and consumer protection, toward the interests of industries and insiders close to the president.\
