Information and memory\'97what the public is told, what is recorded, what is forgotten\'97were contested as fiercely as law and money. The president called for revoking the broadcasting licenses of NBC and ABC, labeling them \'93an arm of the Democrat Party,\'94 and attacked individual commentators who criticized his policies, including a Fox News personality who had argued for stricter gun laws. An FCC commissioner warned that the administration was \'93weaponizing\'94 licensing power, noting that the threat of regulatory retaliation could induce self-censorship in newsrooms. Axios published a glowing account of the first six months of the second Trump term, describing it as highly successful and relying heavily on input from Trump aides, while omitting major controversies such as mass deportations, Medicaid cuts, and pardons related to January 6. Popular Information documented how Sinclair\'92s lead national anchor had resigned over right-wing bias and how corporate headquarters pushed propaganda disguised as local news. At the same time, investigative outlets exposed and helped reverse a Social Security plan to limit phone service, corrected a North Carolina election outcome by uncovering wrongly invalidated ballots, and revealed a Tennessee House speaker\'92s secret home purchase and misuse of per diem funds. The week thus showed both sides of the information struggle: a state leaning on regulators and friendly outlets to shape narratives, and independent journalists still able, in specific cases, to force corrections.\
